''Today is Tuesday'', the 3rd of October.
It rained all day. The storm drains are clogged with leaves and overflowing.

Mr. Mooney came into the geography room five minutes late today and announced we would be writing a test. Of course, there was immediate protest but he wouldn't change his mind and gave us the assignment. Something about Mexico city. |dp>[(link-goto: "David", "Dramatis Personae")] and I had been reading about something else entirely in his textbook and it was still open on the desk.

|c1>[Fearing this might be considered cheating, I closed the book...<br>]\
|c2>[Fearing he might consider it cheating if I touched a page, I...<br>]
---
(align: "==>")[|tp>[]]\
{
(click-replace: ?c1)[Fearing this might be considered cheating, I closed the book. But Mr. Mooney had already spotted it. He came over and told me he was going to mark my test as a fail. I told him I had not been reading about Mexico, but he wouldn't listen. Some people behind me cheered as he confiscated my test.\
	{
	(replace: ?dp)[David]\
	(replace: ?c2)[]\
	(replace: ?tp)[(font: "Times New Roman")[(link-goto: "Continue the diary", "Entry 6A")]]\
	}
]\
(click-replace: ?c2)[Fearing Mooney might consider it cheating if I touched a page, I left it as it was. But as he came strolling down the aisle to look over people's shoulders (why do teachers have to do that, anyway?) he noticed the open book. "What's this? Such brazen cheating! That's a fail for both of you," he went. 

David and I told him we had been reading about India and, looking at the book he said that in that case, it was alright. But then Michael called out from the back of the class, telling him he shouldn't change his judgement and that we'd broken the rules and should get a fail. 

I could see Mr. Mooney was unsure what to do with us. Someone started shouting "Fail! Fail! Fail!" Others fell in. I didn't dare turn around and face them as Mooney confiscated both our tests.\
	{
